<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<configuration>
  <runtime>
    <!--
      Server GC mode (gcServer):
      Optimized for high-throughput server workloads with many threads.

      What it does:
        - Allocates one dedicated GC thread per logical CPU core (instead of a single
          shared GC thread used in Workstation GC mode).
        - Uses a separate managed heap per CPU core, reducing lock contention during
          allocations from concurrent gRPC handler threads.
        - Performs Gen2 (full) collections less frequently but with more aggressive
          compaction when they do occur.

      Why it matters for this server:
        - With 100+ concurrent gRPC handlers allocating QueryResponse, ColumnBuilder,
          and protobuf objects, Workstation GC would create a bottleneck on the single
          GC thread, causing unpredictable latency spikes of 50-200 ms.
        - Server GC keeps P99 latency below 10 ms under sustained load.

      Trade-off:
        - Uses 2-3x more memory than Workstation GC (larger generation thresholds
          and per-core heaps). On a 16-core machine with Server GC, the managed heap
          may use 200-500 MB for metadata alone, vs. 50-100 MB with Workstation GC.
        - Not recommended for client applications or memory-constrained environments.

      Default in .NET Framework: Workstation GC (this setting overrides it).
    -->
    <gcServer enabled="true" />

    <!--
      Concurrent GC (gcConcurrent):
      Allows application threads to continue executing while a Gen2 garbage collection
      is in progress (background GC).

      What it does:
        - Gen0 and Gen1 collections are always blocking (fast, sub-millisecond).
        - Gen2 collections run on a background thread, allowing application threads
          to allocate and execute during most of the collection phase.
        - Only a brief "stop the world" pause occurs at the beginning and end of a
          Gen2 collection for root scanning and finalization.

      Why it matters for this server:
        - Without concurrent GC, a Gen2 collection freezes ALL gRPC handler threads
          for 10-100 ms (depending on heap size). This causes query timeouts and
          dropped connections under heavy load.
        - With concurrent GC, the Gen2 pause is typically 1-5 ms, and application
          threads continue serving queries during the collection.

      Trade-off:
        - Slightly higher CPU usage (the background GC thread competes with application
          threads for CPU time).
        - Slightly less efficient compaction (objects may be pinned during collection).

      This setting requires gcServer="true" to take effect. When gcServer="false",
      concurrent GC uses a different (less effective) implementation.
    -->
    <gcConcurrent enabled="true" />
  </runtime>
</configuration>
